This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with pedestrian action recognition and intention prediction, which are core issues in the field of autonomous driving. Additionally, the paper proposes a model that combines RGB feature information and optical flow feature information, which are commonly used in computer vision tasks. 

The paper is also likely to belong to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category as it focuses on the real-time performance and ultra-low latency of the algorithm, which are important evaluation indicators in the autonomous driving application scenario. 

The paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it mentions the distillation method used to merge the two branches in the training phase. 

The paper could also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category as it deals with the development of algorithms for autonomous driving systems. 

Finally, the paper may belong to the cryptography and security (cs.CR) sub-category as it mentions the importance of the availability and safety of the autonomous driving system, which are related to security concerns.
